1 Overview of workshop

1.1 Objectives

  • To understand the importance of data/analysis transparency and to learn practical data management practices like version control and project directory structure
  • To understand what GitHub is useful for in this regard, and how to use it
  • To learn how to set up a computer for bioinformatic and statistical analyses in R Studio*
  • To learn how to access and retrieve next generation sequencing data from NCBI’s Short Read Archive
  • To understand the data types and structures involved in RNA-seq and differential gene expression analyses; what sequencing reads and gene expression count matrices are, and how to work with them
  • To understand differential gene expression analysis results and how to visualize them to tell a story
  • To learn how to write and work with markdown documents for reproducible data analysis
  • To learn how to utilize publisher-provided LATEX typesets for formatting analyses (and our stories informed by them) for publication.

1.2 Timeline

  • 02/23/21, 3-5pm (EST): Initial setup and discussion about data transparency, management, and reproducibility | Co-hosted by Briana Ezray, Research Data Librarian - STEM, Penn State University Libraries
  • 03/09/21, 3-5pm (EST): RNA-seq analysis, from sequencing reads to gene expression count matrices
  • 03/23/21, 3-5pm (EST): DEG analysis, from count matrices to DEGs (and what they’re good for), and finally,
  • 04/06/21, 3-5pm (EST): Preparing markdown and LATEX documents for scientific communication.

3 Session 1: Initial setup and discussion over data transparency, management, and reproducibility

We will be focusing on data management strategies for a reproducible analysis and output workflow to facilitate transparent and reproducible research as well as support open data sharing.

More specifically, in this session you will learn how to:

  1. Document your data for reusability and structure tabular data for computation.
  2. Manage and organize your files using a project structure.
  3. Utilize the version control software, Git, in the RStudio environment.
  4. Implement a reproducible, project- based, data analysis and output workflow in RStudio.

3.1 Before the workshop:

  1. Register for a free GitHub account (if you do not already have one).
  • You can sign up for GitHub here
  • When creating a username and selecting an email to use consider:
    • Incorporating your actual name or reusing a username from another platform so people easily know whose work they are examining.
    • Picking a username that you would want displayed in a professional context.
    • Making your username widely usable by avoiding using time or place context (for instance, referencing PSU if you will not be here permanently) ( Happy Git and GitHub for the useR by Jennifer Bryan ).
  1. Download and install Git to the computer you plan to use in this workshop.

Windows

Install Git for Windows. Linux

Install Git using the distro’s package manager.

Fedora or RedHat Linux: sudo yum install git

3.2 Data Management Basics

Implementing a project folder structure that you use consistently along with a file naming system is good practice as it allows you to easily navigate project contents.

3.2.1 File and object naming:

Using file and object naming conventions will help you more effectively find and use your data.

Some naming best practices include:

  • Create brief yet meaningful names
  • Avoid using spaces, dots, and special characters (&, ?, !), instead use hypthens (-) or underscores (-)
  • When files are linked in a workflow, number them to indicate the order they should be run
  • Denote versioning where appropriate

3.2.2 Project Structure:

Project structure and descriptions adapted from Cookiecutter Data Science, R Best Practices by Krista L. DeStasio), & project_template GitHub repository - Drew Wham

Below is an example project folder structure:

Named_Project/

|–README.md

|–R_Project

|–volume/

| |–data/

| | |–raw

| | |–interim

| | |–external

|–required

| |–requirements.R

|–source_code/

|–documents/

|–figures/

|–output/

|–.gitignore

  • Named_Project: Root level folder denoting the project. This folder contains all folders and files related to the project and is checked into GitHub.
  • README.md: Top-level README file outlining folder structure and files as well as file associations.
  • R_Project: A R_Project file.
  • Volume: A folder containing your data subset by type. This folder will not be uploaded to Github thus we will .gitignore it.
  • Data: This folder contains data subfolders. Within this folder, are the data you will use for analysis. - Raw: Raw data files used in the project. These files should be treated as read-only and never altered. - Interim: Intermediate data that has been wrangled or transformed. - External: Data from third-party sources.
  • Required: The required libraries for reproducing the R environment.
  • Source_code: Source code or scripts for running data wrangling, analysis, and visualization.
  • Documents: Generated documents for final reporting of the project such as manuscripts or reports.
  • Figures: Generated figures for final reporting of the project. This should only contain figures generated by your saved source code.
  • Output: Non-figure objects created by your source code including processed data, logs, simulation output, or model output.
  • .gitignore: List of files not to sync with GitHub.

3.2.3 Setting up a RStudio Project

Why use a RStudio Project?

Using a RStudio Project is an easy way to keep everything you need for your analysis together in a manner that is reproducible and shareable.

It is best practice to avoid using absolute paths, such as those implemented using the setwd() approach, because the link to this location can easily be broken and is not easily reproduced by others. Jenny Bryan explains this by stating “The chance of the setwd() command having the desired effect - making the file paths work - for anyone besides it’s author is 0%. It’s also unlikely to work for the author one or two years or computers from now. The project is not self-contained and portable. To recreate and perhaps extend this plot, the lucky recipient will need to hand edit one or more paths to reflect where the project has landed on their machine” ( Project-oriented workflow by Jenny Bryan )

Using RStudio Projects allows you to use relative paths rather than absolute paths and store settings for a particular project. An RStudio Project relative path points to the top level folder where your .Rproj file is located.

How to set up an RStudio Project:

  1. Click the R Project: (None) button in the top right corner of the RStudio console.
  2. Select New Directory
  3. Select New Project
  4. Give your directory a name and locate where on your computer you want this project directory and RStudio project to be stored
  5. Click Create Project
3.2.3.0.1 Exercise 1:
  1. Navigate to your project folder on your desktop. Look through each of the folders and consider what you would put in each.
  2. Open RStudio and using the below directions, designate this folder as your project folder.
    • Open RStudio.
    • Click the RProject button in the top right of the console.
    • Select New Project.
    • Select Existing Directory.
    • Browse to the Project folder on your Desktop and select this folder.
    • Click Create Project.

3.3 Key Elements For Good R Code

  1. It is a bad habit to rely on the settings of a previous RStudio session. To prevent RStudio from saving your settings from a previous session, you can change the following setting:
  • Find your preferences in RStudio
  • Under the general tab
    • Uncheck “Restore .RData”
    • Select “never” for Save workspace…

( R for Data Science by Wickham & Grolemund, Project-oriented workflow by Jenny Bryan )

  1. Make your code readable.
  • Organize your code to make it more readable.
    • Start your code with a brief description of what it does.
    • Make run requirements and dependencies clear by putting library() loading and functions at the top.
  • Use comments to describe the purpose of the code
  • Use meaningful object naming
  • Use version control
  • Adopt a coding style

( Why I want to write nice R cod by Daniel Falster, R Best Practices by Krista L. DeStasio )

  1. Make your code reliable
  • Check that your code is error free

( Why I want to write nice R cod by Daniel Falster )

3.4 Version Control with Git and GitHub

Instructions below are either from or adapted from Happy Git and GitHub for the useR by Jennifer Bryan.

3.4.1 Configure Git with your user credentials:

*Windows users will want to use the Git Bash shell!

In the shell or terminal, type the following with your name and email as they are associated with your GitHub account:

git config --global user.name ‘enteryournamehere’

git config --global user.email ‘enteryouremailhere’

Confirm that you have configured Git with your credentials, using the following code in the shell or terminal:

Git config --global --list

3.4.2 Connect to GitHub:

  1. Login to GitHub at https://github.com
  2. Create a new repository by either clicking the “New repository” button or from your personal profile clicking “Repositories” > “New”
  3. You will be prompted to:
    • Name your repository: Set your repository name to “CFH_RWorkshop2”
    • Add a description: Include the following text: “testing setup”
    • Select private as the visibility
    • Select to initialize this repository with a README
  4. Create the repository
  5. By clicking the “Clone or Download” button, copy the HTTPS clone URL.

3.4.3 Clone GitHub repository on your computer in RStudio:

  1. Open RStudio
  2. Start a new project in RStudio: File > New Project > Version Control > Git.
  3. Under “Repository URL,” paste the copy of the HTTPS clone URL for your GitHub repository you created above.
  4. Check that the default project directory name matches the name of your GitHub repository and accept.
  5. Note where the R Project will be saved locally.
  6. Select “Open in new session”
  7. Click “Create Project”
  8. Check that you can see the GitHub README.md in the RStudio file browser pane.
  • Connecting RStudio to Git can be complicated because of variability between operating systems and versions of operating systems. To confirm that Git properly setup, follow the following steps:

Mac OS

  1. In RStudio, select Preferences > Git/SVN
  2. Check to see if a path to a file in the Git executable window exists.
  3. If not, return to your shell or terminal and type which git. This will produce the path to your Git executable if it is installed.
  4. Type or paste in the full path to your git executable: e.g. /usr/bin/git into the Git executable box on R Studio Git/SVN screen.

Windows

  1. In RStudio, Go Tools > Global options > Git/SVN
  2. Check to see if a path to a file in the Git executable window exists.
  3. If not, return to your shell or terminal and type which git. This will produce the path to your Git executable if it is installed.
  4. Type or paste in the full path to your git executable: e.g. /usr/bin/git into the Git executable box on R Studio Git/SVN screen.
  • If Git is still not properly connected, following this link to see steps to troubleshoot.

3.4.4 Make local changes, save, and commit to Git:

  1. In RStudio, add the line “This is a line from RStudio” in the README.md file and click save
  2. Click the “Git” tab in the upper right pane
  3. Check “Staged” box for README.md
  4. If you’re not already in the Git pop-up, click “Commit.”
  5. Type a message in “Commit message,” such as “Commit from RStudio.”
  6. Click “Commit”

3.4.5 Push your local changes online to GitHub:

  1. Click the green “Push” button to send your local changes online at GitHub.
  2. Go to GitHub online to confirm that the local change was submitted to GitHub online.

4 Session 2: RNA-seq analysis, from sequencing reads to gene expression count matrices

4.1 Example experiment

In this session, we will retrieve (a subset of) sequencing reads from an RNA-seq experiment exploring tissue-specific gene expression profiles of nurse, forager, and winter honey bees. The goal of this experiment was to test hypotheses about the relationship between the winter bee phenotype and diapause, a genetically programmed state of dormancy which is triggered by environmental cues in advance of adverse conditions, such as winter in temperate areas or hot and dry conditions in tropical areas (Denlinger & Armbruster, 2013; Saulich & Musolin, 2017; Sim & Denlinger, 2013). The physiology of winter worker bees (and long-lived summer bees) suggest that they are in a diapause-like state [see Bresnahan et al. in prep… i.e., hopefully someday soon :) ]

4.2 Methods

Sample collection was conducted as described in Doke et al. (2020) (Doke et al., 2019). Briefly, four colonies headed by naturally mated honey bee queens from four different commercial breeders were established at a Pennsylvania State University apiary in central Pennsylvania. Colonies were maintained according to standard apicultural practices. More than 6 weeks after establishment (July 2013), which is sufficient time for the eggs laid by the queens to develop into adult nurses and foragers, 6 summer nurse and forager bees per colony were collected on dry ice and stored at -80\(^\circ\)C. Winter bees were collected 5 months later (December 2013) from within their respective winter clusters.

After removal from storage at -80\(^\circ\)C, sampled bees were submerged in Invitrogen\(^{TM}\) Ambion\(^{TM}\) RNAlater\(^{TM}\) Stabilization Solution (ThermoFisher Scientific) to prevent RNA degradation, and dissected on a platform surrounded by dry ice. To collect flight muscle tissue, legs and wings were detached from thorax and discarded, leaving flight muscles and exoskeleton. To collect abdominal fat body tissues, abdomens were allowed to thaw RNAlater\(^{TM}\) on ice. Digestive tracts and reproductive organs were then removed by gently pulling from the stinger using forceps, leaving the eviscerated abdomen with fat body. Dissected tissues for each worker were individually placed in a 1.5ml nuclease-free microcentrifuge tube (Denville Scientific Inc., Metuchen, NJ) and kept at -80\(^\circ\)C.

For each of the 4 colonies, samples of the same tissue and bee type were pooled (6 bees per sample). Pooled samples (4 colonies x 3 groups x 2 tissues = 24 samples, total) were homogenized using an automated homogenizer (Thermo Savant FastPrep\(^{TM}\) FP120 Cell Disrupter System) for 3 intervals of 45 seconds at the highest speed setting, using 3-6 2mm zirconia bees (BioSpec Products, Inc.). Homogenates were stored for later use in RNA extraction via the RNeasy Plus Universal kit (QIAGEN) for RNA sequencing (RNA-seq). RNA libraries were prepared by the Sequencing and Genomic Technologies Shared Resource at the Duke Center for Genomic and Computational Biology, Durham, NC, and sequenced on an Illumina HiSeq 4000 platform.

4.3 Methods (ClEaRlY eXpLaInEd)

4.4 Setup

4.4.1 Bash (*the catch)

Alright, I hate to tell you this, but, no matter how hard you try to avoid it you will need to set a few things up in bash (if using a Mac, you can work in bash via Terminal). The algorithms used to align NGS reads to a reference genome are simply too resource intensive to implement in R directly, and many excellent command line tools are readily available to download and install. To make things easier for us, we will use a package management system (Conda) which will effectively reduce the number of opportunities for Murphy’s law to manifest. The second half of this workshop covers the world of R Markdown, wherein bash code chunks can be written and run while knitting the markdown document. Therefore it is technically possible to complete the entirety of RNA-seq and DEG analysis within R… once you know things will run smoothly in bash :) More on this later…

4.4.1.1 Conda

Download an installer for Miniconda here. Follow the instructions, then open a Terminal window once installation completes.

After installing conda you will need to add the bioconda channel as well as the other channels bioconda depends on. It is important to add them in this order so that the priority is set correctly (that is, conda-forge is highest priority).

The conda-forge channel contains many general-purpose packages not already found in the defaults channel. In your terminal:

conda config --add channels defaults
conda config --add channels bioconda
conda config --add channels conda-forge

Now, we need to create a Conda “environment” in which to install a few bioinformatics tools:

conda create -n bioinformatics

Each time you open a new Terminal window, it is operating within a base environment called .bash_profile. We want to work within our new bioinformatics Conda environment:

conda activate bioinformatics

Next, we can install most of the tools we need directly through Conda. The first of these tools are called samtools and bedtools, suites of programs for interacting with high-throughput sequencing data and for conducting operations on genomic intervals. We won’t use them directly in this workshop, but they are often prerequisite for other bioinformatics tools. Next, we will use NCBI’s SRA-toolkit to interface with SRA.

conda install -c bioconda samtools

conda install -c bioconda bedtools

conda install -c bioconda sra-tools

4.4.1.2 Command line tools

Additionally, we will install trim_galore, and kallisto. Trim_galore is a wrapper program around cutadapt - which is used to trim sequencing adapters from sequencing reads (more on this later) - and FastQC - which creates reports detailing quality control metrics of the sequencing reads (more on this later, too). Kallisto is the tool we will use to generate transcript abundance estimates for calculating gene expression. To install trim_galore and kallisto, follow each link (above) and associated download and install instructions.
